"Geiser F., Turbill C.","Hibernation and daily torpor minimize mammalian extinctions",2009,"Naturwissenschaften","96","10",,"1235","1240",,,10.1007/s00114-009-0583-0,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70349603040&partnerID=40&md5=9de7f294f9635c8d8a683736629ac3b8","Centre for Behavioural and Physiological Ecology, Zoology, University of New England, Armidale NSW 2351, Australia; Research Institute of Wildlife Ecology, University of Veterinary Medicine, Vienna 1160, Austria","Geiser, F., Centre for Behavioural and Physiological Ecology, Zoology, University of New England, Armidale NSW 2351, Australia; Turbill, C., Research Institute of Wildlife Ecology, University of Veterinary Medicine, Vienna 1160, Austria","Small mammals appear to be less vulnerable to extinction than large species, but the underlying reasons are poorly understood. Here, we provide evidence that almost all (93.5%) of 61 recently extinct mammal species were homeothermic, maintaining a constant high body temperature and thus energy expenditure, which demands a high intake of food, long foraging times, and thus exposure to predators. In contrast, only 6.5% of extinct mammals were likely heterothermic and employed multi-day torpor (hibernation) or daily torpor, even though torpor is widespread within more than half of all mammalian orders. Torpor is characterized by substantial reductions of body temperature and energy expenditure and enhances survival during adverse conditions by minimizing food and water requirements, and consequently reduces foraging requirements and exposure to predators. Moreover, because life span is generally longer in heterothermic mammals than in related homeotherms, heterotherms can employ a 'sit-and-wait' strategy to withstand adverse periods and then repopulate when circumstances improve. Thus, torpor is a crucial but hitherto unappreciated attribute of small mammals for avoiding extinction. Many opportunistic heterothermic species, because of their plastic energetic requirements, may also stand a better chance of future survival than homeothermic species in the face of greater climatic extremes and changes in environmental conditions caused by global warming. © 2009 Springer-Verlag.","Energy expenditure; Foraging requirements; Global warming; Survival rates; Unpredictable climate","bioenergetics; body temperature; environmental conditions; extinction; food intake; hibernation; small mammal; survival; article; body temperature; energy expenditure; fluid intake; greenhouse effect; hibernation; nonhuman; species extinction; survival rate; Animals; Australia; Body Size; Body Temperature; Body Temperature Regulation; Energy Metabolism; Extinction, Biological; Hibernation; Mammals; Motor Activity; Species Specificity; Mammalia",,,,,,"Bieber, C., Ruf, T., Summer dormancy in edible dormice (Glis glis) without energetic constraints (2009) Naturwissenschaften, 96, pp. 165-171. , 19034404 10.1007/s00114-008-0471-z 1:CAS:528:DC%2BD1cXhsV2qu77L; Boyer, B.B., Barnes, B.M., Molecular and metabolic aspects of mammalian hibernation (1999) Bioscience, 49, pp. 713-724. , 10.2307/1313595; Cardillo, M., Biological determinants of extinction risk: Why are smaller species less vulnerable? (2003) Animal Conservation, 6 (1), pp. 63-69. , DOI 10.1017/S1367943003003093; Cardillo, M., MacE, G.M., Gittleman, J.M., Purvis, A., Latent extinction risk and future battlegrounds of mammal conservation (2006) Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A, 103, pp. 4157-4161. , 16537501 10.1073/pnas.0510541103 1:CAS:528:DC%2BD28XivFWiurc%3D; Carey, H.V., Andrews, M.T., Martin, S.L., Mammalian hibernation: Cellular and molecular responses to depressed metabolism and low temperature (2003) Physiol Rev, 83, pp. 1153-1181. , 14506303 1:CAS:528:DC%2BD3sXoslyjsbo%3D; Ceballos, G., Ehrlich, P.R., Mammal population losses and the extinction crisis (2002) Science, 296 (5569), pp. 904-907. , DOI 10.1126/science.1069349; Cooper, C.E., Geiser, F., The ""minimal boundary curve for endot